data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## The Problem

In C# 14 / .NET 10, new **span overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of the old `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Since `MemoryExtensions.Contains` is not representable in expression trees, this throws at runtime.

## The Fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` to force the correct overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three options force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is expression-tree compatible.
